// TEST: stdlib_compare_output_smoke
// EXPECT: output "equal"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// A `main` that builds two equal `Key`s via `core.compare.key(...)` and prints
// whether they are `eq`. The conformance harness executes this against every
// present target toolchain; it is additionally validated by the CLI-level
// `bock run` smoke test in bock-cli's `stdlib_compare` integration suite,
// which asserts this exact "equal" output against the real interpreter.
//
// `rust` was previously excluded (Q-rust-equatable-eq-collision, a loud skip
// added by #372): `Key` carries an explicit `impl Equatable`, so the rust
// backend emits both `impl Equatable for Key` (its `eq`) and a DQ31
// delegating `impl PartialEq for Key`. A value-receiver `a.eq(&b)` was then
// ambiguous between `Equatable::eq` and `PartialEq::eq` (E0034). The rust
// backend now lowers a `.eq` on an explicit-`impl Equatable` user type to the
// fully-qualified trait call `Equatable::eq(&a, &b)`; rust is back in the set.
//
// The smoke uses `.eq(...)` (whose impl body returns a Bool) rather than
// `.compare(...)`: constructing an enum variant inside a *cross-module* stdlib
// impl body is an interpreter-scoping gap (the variant name is undefined at
// run time), tracked separately from type-checking and codegen, both of which
// handle it. See the session's PR notes.
module main

use core.compare.{Key, key}

public fn main() {
  let a = key(2)
  let b = key(2)
  if (a.eq(b)) {
    println("equal")
  } else {
    println("differ")
  }
}
